# Fluff Date: 2026-02-19 16:29:24
overview:<p>The Shogun traces its origins to the final years of the Star League, when Mitchell Vehicles of Graham IV began production of this eighty-five-ton assault BattleMech in 2777. Designed as a highly survivable multi-role assault platform, the Shogun was conceived to share key components with the widely produced Stalker, including its engine and gyroscope, simplifying logistics for Star League Defense Force units. The addition of jump jets set the Shogun apart from most assault-class designs, providing exceptional tactical flexibility in urban combat environments.</p><p>Despite its promising design, the Shogun saw limited production before the devastation of the First Succession War destroyed the Graham IV factory. The design languished in obscurity for centuries until Wolf's Dragoons arrived in the Inner Sphere in 3005, fielding Shoguns in their feared Zeta Battalion. Clan Sea Fox later revived full-scale production at their Tukayyid facilities, ensuring the Shogun's legacy endures into the ilClan era.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Shogun's initial requirements called for a highly survivable multi-role assault platform, and the design delivers on that promise. The Strand 255 engine propels the eighty-five-ton chassis to a modest fifty-four kilometers per hour, but the inclusion of Anderson Propulsion 21 jump jets grants the Shogun a ninety-meter leaping capability that most assault BattleMechs simply cannot match. This combination of mass, firepower, and mobility makes the Shogun particularly effective in urban combat, where its jump capability allows it to traverse obstacles that would channel slower assault designs into kill zones.</p><p>The SHG-2F mounts a Magna Firestar extended-range particle projection cannon as its primary weapon, capable of engaging targets at extreme distances. Twin Coventry Star Fire LRM racks provide sustained fire support, while a pair of Thunderstroke SRM-6 launchers deliver devastating close-range salvos to exploit weakened armor. Shogun pilots historically coordinated with infantry units in urban environments, using the LRM racks to suppress distant targets before closing to short range with jump jets to deliver punishing missile volleys.</p><p>However, the design's reliance on ammunition-dependent weapons creates a notable vulnerability during extended engagements, and spare parts have been chronically scarce throughout the Shogun's operational history. The chassis also suffers from difficult maintenance requirements and non-standard components, a legacy of its limited production run and the unique Kitushi frame.</p>

deployment:<p>The SHG-2H is the original Star League Defense Force variant, first produced in 2777 at Mitchell Vehicles on Graham IV. Compared to the later SHG-2F, the 2H features several notable improvements including Armorscale ferro-fibrous armor with CASE protection, Artemis IV fire control systems on both LRM-15 racks, and four Defiance Streak SRM-2 launchers replacing the heavier SRM-6 systems. A head-mounted Blankenburg medium pulse laser and a Magna Mk. II medium laser in the center torso provide additional close-range firepower that later Dragoon variants sacrificed. With only eight production runs completed before the Exodus and the subsequent destruction of the Graham IV factory, surviving SHG-2H models are extraordinarily rare relics of the Star League era.</p>

history:<p>The Shogun's history is one of near-extinction and remarkable revival. The design was commissioned during the waning years of the Star League, with the original requirements for a highly survivable assault BattleMech first published by the SLDF in the late 26th century. By the time the Shogun project entered its design phase in 2771, the requirements had evolved to address critical weaknesses in the Stalker chassis while maintaining component commonality. Mitchell Vehicles on Graham IV was awarded the production contract, and the first SHG-2H models rolled off the assembly line in 2777.</p><p>Production was tragically brief. The Shogun could well have supplanted the Stalker as the SLDF's premier assault BattleMech, but Kerensky's Exodus intervened. After the SLDF recaptured Graham IV, Mitchell Vehicles completed just eight production runs prior to the Exodus, and only a few additional units were built before the factory was destroyed during the early part of the First Succession War. The success and wide proliferation of the Stalker filled the role the Shogun was meant for, and the outbreak of the Reunification War and the peace of the Star League's Golden Age saw the original design requirements shelved. General Kerensky's war to liberate Terra demanded a replacement assault BattleMech to refill SLDF ranks, giving the Shogun its brief window of production.</p><p>The Shogun was thought lost to the Free Worlds League military after the fall of the Star League, its few surviving examples scattered and forgotten. The design's dramatic reappearance came with the arrival of Wolf's Dragoons in the Inner Sphere in 3005. The mysterious mercenary unit fielded several Shoguns in their elite Zeta Battalion, shocking observers who recognized the ancient assault design. During the Dragoons' pre-Clan years, Shoguns were found almost exclusively within Zeta Battalion, and the few examples encountered outside the famed mercenary unit were either hard-fought salvage or extremely rare Free Worlds League family heirlooms.</p><p>Wolf's Dragoons attempted to secure production through negotiations with manufacturers including Blackwell Corporation, but the custom-built Kitushi frame proved impossible to replicate. After the brutal losses on Misery, Shoguns became rare even among the rebuilt Dragoons and were increasingly reserved for static fire and artillery lances rather than frontline assault operations. By the late 3050s, reliable intelligence estimates placed the total number of operational Shoguns, all variants including the rare Clan modification, at only six. Negotiations between Blackwell, operating on behalf of the Dragoons, and the government on Graham IV ended in repeated failure, all but guaranteeing the design's extinction.</p><p>The Word of Blake's devastation of Outreach in 3068 further reduced the surviving population. Dragoon survivors who evacuated from Outreach with assistance from Wolf-in-Exile forces in 3068 managed to preserve some of the Dragoons' technological know-how, but not the engineering and design specifications for the Shogun. With much of Outreach reduced to radioactive ruins, only two Shoguns were confirmed to survive in any standing army, both salvaged from the remains of a Dragoon supply depot and reportedly in the hands of Wannamaker's Widowmakers.</p><p>The Shogun's fortunes changed dramatically when Clan Sea Fox recognized the design's commercial potential. Leveraging their manufacturing facilities at Manufacturing Plant SFF-TU1 on Tukayyid, Clan Sea Fox began producing new Shogun variants around 3090, starting with the SHG-3E, an Inner Sphere technology version designed for the mercenary market. The original Clan-tech Shogun C had existed since the Golden Century, when the few Clans that still possessed Shoguns gave the design a comprehensive overhaul using newly developed technologies, but full-scale factory production had never been established until Clan Sea Fox's initiative. Subsequent variants including the C 2 and C 3 continued to expand the Shogun's capabilities, with the C 3 competing directly in the same assault niche as the venerable Warhawk. Clan Sea Fox merchants found particular success marketing these designs in Lyran space and across the occupation zones, ensuring that this ancient assault design continues to stride across battlefields well into the ilClan era.</p>

